Hey friends, I've been asked to sit on a stage!

I've been working on a project with @[100000665846696:2048:Alix.MDUONEIL], @[100000215177113:2048:CSOER.GNIK] and @[776235037:2048:Ge Roge] called Ethi :D it's short for ethical, and it's about making our personal data useful for us, not just companies. You can find it at ethi.me (still in development!).

We want to help people understand and control their data. We're starting with a web-app which analyses and visualises your Facebook data - a couple of highlights we're looking at:
1. How your personal security is impacted by the data you share online, and 2. analysing your mood over time to understand how social media can affect it.

Project Access - an amazing organisation that helps underprivileged young people get into top universities - thought our project fitted really well with their "Tech and Ethics" panel, and invited me to join that discussion, which I think is cool af.

I think Project Access is brilliant, and the conference has some much more impressive people speaking at it than me, from Partners at Deloitte to Geopolitical analysts. It'll be a super interesting day. Please come along and clap extra hard if I say anything interesting!

Mucho love xx

If you've been thinking about authenticity and coffee shops, or wondering about self-deprecation and self-awareness as artistic tools to optimise against criticism: this is an article so thoughtful I wish I had written it (I didn't).

TL:DR selected quotes (my titles):

The melancholy of pure aestheticism:
"I find myself hoping that someoneâs read those books, or at least intended to, because that would mean theyâre here for a reason other than the aesthetic. But they look bone-dry and dusty like the top of the dresser in the spare room of my grandparentsâ house, and theyâre in a cafÃ©, not a library. Next to those books are speakers from a different era that might still work but probably donât."

Self-reflection on the cynicism of assuming inauthenticity:
"As I sit, I can feel the shop wondering why I sit here judging it, unwilling to admit that a cafÃ© might just be a cafÃ©, or that this chair might just be a chair. And as I enter minute 100 or so, sniffing around for inauthenticity, it occurs to me that Iâve been doing this the whole trip, and perhaps my whole life, so intent on finding the hypocrisy or hidden agendas in everyone and everything that I neglect to simply take things as they are."

Authenticity is necessarily eroded by markets
"We appear to have reached a point where authenticity has become so marketable that the delay between a trait existing authentically and being identified and reclaimed by the markets is so small that it may as well not exist." 

Self-reflection on this piece's authenticity or lack of it
"I am left wondering, too, if I am that person, or just another in a long line of them; if this essay is nothing more than a written version of the same aesthetic I observe in this cafÃ©, a response to the marketâs demand for pieces critical of the decided lack of authenticity in coffee shops the world over."

title: ACWBUYF.XYFFS wrote on Anja Johnson's Timeline.

data.post:
Panama now Paradise. If you haven't heard. Moneyyyy.

More people not paying their tax, causing the deficit, creating poverty, a system that has had no attempt made to reform things, to stop this. A Brexit that is looking like it's designed primarily for disaster capitalists (things get cheap in crises, so if you have money can buy up more things) to exploit, perhaps even designed by disaster capitalists looking at the big political donors using tax haven money to buy influence, money4influence.politics.come.on. In terms of wages vs gdp growth, Britain is the only country where workers got poorer as the country got richer from 2007-15. A financial crisis caused by moral hazard in the highly paid banking sector get's blamed on Labour, when it's the banks who messed with other people's money? Giving out dead in the water mortgages and selling them on as "low risk" "AAA" for a tidy profit? And then austerity's burden is placed on the disadvantaged who didn't cause the problem, while corporate taxes are cut with some trickle down magic idea that this will help.

We ignore Nobel prize winning economists, ignore new analysis from the IMF that inequality is now so great it's impeding growth, ignore the fact that the wealthiest 1% doubled their wealth since the financial crisis while the bottom 80% are about where they were before, spend money on Buckingham Palace in the midst of the worst housing crisis since London's residential areas were literally bombsites, with almost 0 public housing construction having taken place since council houses were sold off with no effort to replenish the supply.

"Let me be clear" now means "Allow me to be attempt misdirection", all the chat about stopping tax avoidance and tax havens is a smokescreen that combines with the colourful tinted glass of "we want to help working people, BRitISh Values, red white and blue" to try to hide what is really going on. I don't remember there being this many homeless people on the streets of London in 2010, and it's true, numbers have more than doubled. Support isn't there. Universal credit takes six weeks to begin, from people living on the breadline already. One in four UK families have less than Â£95 in savings.

In other News:
"Two-thirds of domestic violence shelters facing closure due to welfare cuts, research suggests" - Independent. 2016
"Benefit cuts will increase child poverty, Forecast 31.3% of children will be in poverty by 2021-22, highest level since 2003" - FT, IFS. 2017

This just isn't the way to run a country. I think there is plenty evidence that generosity and success can go together. I think that children need education that can compete with the world. And food on the table. Meanness, austerity and scapegoating? Or social democracy, using capitalism for good, following Sweden's footsteps, with extra lessons from Germany. Maybe we give that a try next time.

Fanks xx

data.post:
Politics, Sociology and Psychology needs studying in order to improve our societies and democracies. I'm running a pilot for a UK Citizen Politics Survey to be conducted next year at UCL, and I'm looking for respondents (UK citizens only, sorry!).

It's about 5-7 minutes long, and there's a short quiz on a variety of political topics which should be interesting/fun to take part in (you get a score out of 25 and can see what you got wrong) and then a survey of satisfaction and engagement. The survey will form part of an action proposal to improve the state of politics and political discourse in the UK, which I'm sure we all would like to see. event.description:
I figured we should all get together for an evening before we all break up for Christmas. My halls has a bar that serves Â£1 Budweisers, Â£1.50 Coronas and Â£2.50 Vodka mixers. We also have a table tennis table (did I hear someone say beer pong?), table football and a pool table too. Also if we do it here I don't have to move. 

As I'm sure (I hope) you are all aware, the fantastic (free) Friday night institution of ULU is just round the corner from UCL, and conveniently, so is my halls, so I figured we could all come here for drinks from 8-11pm (when the bar closes), and then those who wanted to come to ULU could then do so.

Because the bar is properly licensed and stuff, you can't drink your own drinks in the bar area until it closes at 11, but if you want to save some money (i.e. Â£1 a beer was too steep for your budget), then feel free to bring a few bits for post bar and pre-ULU from 11.00-11.30.

Looking forward to seeing you all there, let me know soon-ish if you can come so I can tell the bar manager how many bar staff will be needed!

I've decided to unlike your page because of the grating tabloid journalism techniques you are employing.
